text:
come, sit beside me

tell me how do i look, 
too tired or too plastic?

look into my eyes, 
do they look too dry 
or do they look like
they're still holding 
an ocean more of tears behind them

run your finger over my wrinkled heart, 
which has become too old, too early, 
hold it, i say, hold it carefully
and tell me, 
does it weigh heavy? is it still carrying the weight of those sulky memories

run your fingers through my skin and feel the scars, 
do they still weep over the stories which died few years ago? 
or are they dying to breathe? 
swallow my fears, and tell me how they taste, like my experiences or regrets

hug me and see, do my arms have any energy left, to hold someone tight, close and safe? 
look at my hands, do they look like they're still willing to hold other? or they still look young?

look at my lips, do they look like they have much to say, or they've surrendered to the numbness that the heart carries?

for once, listen to my silence, and tell me, does it still scream or it has given up?

come, sit beside me 
and tell me how do i look? 
do i look tired, 
or am i still good at faking it?
~ kalyani kulkarni

text:
about the creative process of playwright @argiacoppola’s stage adaptation of blonde, the pulitzer prize finalist novel by @joycecaroloates.

in this extract from her interview with @corriere corriere della sera, la lettura (november 17th, 2017), @argiacoppola talks about the intimate connection she feels with marilyn, and the importance of her life story:

marilyn uses her imagination to change reality and to react to pain in an unexpected way. i felt an immediate connection, and in that moment, i decided that her story was an important one to tell for women today; that she was a misunderstood woman, never got (as is often the case for women), different from what the world believed. i was happy to discover, during a recent dinner with oates, that she thought of it the same way. when i read the first words of her novel, “and then came death…” i understood that i would not have been able to write a new text without this novel. i feel a profound gratitude to this great author for having written such an extensive, powerful, complex work.” _______________

want to delve deeper into our world? keep following, and discover our #crowdfunding now running on the #linkinbio. contribute any way you can: every dollar counts! if we don’t reach the final amount, we won’t keep any donation made, and our dream of taking marilyn’s untold truth to broadway will be halted.

text: i am so thrilled to share a project with you all that just came out in this month's elle magazine. this summer i had the great privilege to photograph 12 courageous and inspiring women for elle. this project, titled 'the replacements' is a series of portraits outstanding women who have taken over the jobs of men who were outed during the #metoo movement. spanning from hollywood to politics and beyond, these women have boldly ascended. as both a woman and a photographer i could not be more proud to have been chosen to shoot this project- i am humbled and inspired. thank you  thank you lauren, martin, and katelyn. you three nothing short of incredible. thank you to all of the amazingly gifted stylists, hair and makeup artists, and assistants who worked so hard on this project. you all are gold. thank you violet o'neill and oliphant studios for your generosity and support. @laurenwbrown @katelynmbaker @anatolli @campbellritchie @elleusa @ninagarcia @robingwright @sarahschussheim @kendalmaeboyle @riadazar9 @maggiebullock @oliphantstudio @violet_ohoh @spyderman31 @aprilblumphoto

text: i have been absent from not only social media lately but a lot of other aspects of my life. i know it was for a good cause though. the last two weekends i was given yet another opportunity to partake in the #metoo survivor circle stories. i don’t think i realized what it would feel like for me to tell me story that many times. i am exhausted, vulnerable, and thankful for the opportunity. i know the value of speaking of my story and speaking my truth. but i also know it feels like very intensive exposure therapy as the cast came to deem it. and it has truly caused some shifts in my thinking. that what happened to me was not a scene from a movie but a real life experience. it has been hard for me to come to this realization. to realize i am human and mortal and during that portion of time i was in a life or death situation. so thank you to my survivors sisters who were with me during this process and gave me their shoulders to cry on, thank you to my fiancé for just staying home with me when i needed it, and thank you to playbuilders for giving me this opportunity. #metoo #hawaii #playbuilders #survivor #survivorstories

text:
⬇️what i learned from taking risks ⬇️
💢
i used to be a "box checker." society made these goals and i was gona acheive them! get my diploma, check✔get my degree, check✔! land my career that is a result of my degree, check!! ✔
💢
but then... my job didn't make me happy. and the job after that didn't make me happy either. i felt like a failure. why could everyone find and keep a job for 30+ years and retire? yet no matter how many times i moved, i wasnt happy.
💢
each time i found that i was internally unhappy, i recognized that i was not following my soul, my purpose. and each time i felt uneasy, i found the courage to let go and move!!!
💢
eventually, i realized that i had been living up to what was expected of me, rather than following my own calling and purpose. but i also discovered that each time i made a courageous change to a new job, i felt better! 💢
i continued to take baby steps and follow my inner voice to what felt right to me. 💢
i refused to stay at a job because it was the most money i'd ever made. my happiness came first. i didn't settle for a place with people that did not respect and appreciate me. i chose to put myself and my happiness first!
💢
taking risks is scary, but i can promise that no matter how it turns out, it is always worth it. you will always find yourself just a little (if not a whole lot) closer to what your calling is; your soul's purpose. your joy!
💢
quit that job you dread going to, find a better one! dabble in activities you enjoy and explore how you can make a career out of your passion! take that class you're interested in. whatever it is, go!!!
💢
as long as you feel that longing inside, it is your soul nudging you to move and follow your heart. it is for a reason.
💢
you'll never grow if you don't move. and as long as you're taking steps towards your happiness, you're growing! that's the beauty of it🌱💜
💢
dm me to learn more about working with me 1:1 and beginning to tap into your true purpose 💜🧚🏽‍♀️

but then... my job didn't make me happy. and the job after that didn't make me happy either. i felt like a failure. why could everyone find and keep a job for 30+ years and retire? yet no matter how many times i moved, i wasnt happy.
💢
each time i found that i was internally unhappy, i recognized that i was not following my soul, my purpose. and each time i felt uneasy, i found the courage to let go and move!!!
💢
eventually, i realized that i had been living up to what was expected of me, rather than following my own calling and purpose. but i also discovered that each time i made a courageous change to a new job, i felt better! 💢
i continued to take baby steps and follow my inner voice to what felt right to me. 💢
i refused to stay at a job because it was the most money i'd ever made. my happiness came first. i didn't settle for a place with people that did not respect and appreciate me. i chose to put myself and my happiness first!
💢
taking risks is scary, but i can promise that no matter how it turns out, it is always worth it. you will always find yourself just a little (if not a whole lot) closer to what your calling is; your soul's purpose. your joy!
💢
quit that job you dread going to, find a better one! dabble in activities you enjoy and explore how you can make a career out of your passion! take that class you are interested in. whatever it is, go!!!
💢
as long as you feel that longing inside, it is your soul nudging you to move and follow your heart. it is for a reason.
💢
you'll never grow if you do not move. and as long as you are taking steps towards your happiness, you are growing! that's the beauty of it🌱💜
💢
dm me to learn more about working with me 1:1 and beginning to tap into your true purpose 💜🧚🏽‍♀️

text:
god first the rest will follow…💜
.
how many times have i read those words? it wasn’t until i learned this truth, when i really dissected it and took it apart to put it back together….i was able to breathe a sigh of relief.
.
not just at having received such a revelation but to step out & put it into practice. you see i had become a control ‘freak’. i figured if i can control the situation, if i can control this person, if i can control the outcome…control this…control that…do you see how exhausting it is just reading that sentence?! yikes!
.
i was really putting myself first. granted it came from a deep rooted place of fear, self-hatred, anxiety, & vulnerability. it was my way of protecting myself from past traumas. the more i tried to control things, the less i could control. being in a constant state of tense fight or flight mode is no way to live.
.
‘for god has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.‘ 2 timothy 1:7 . -this has become one of my power verses. it gives me strength when i feel myself slipping back into that dark place.
.
i have gradually made it a consistent practice to begin each day at 5am meditating on the word in quiet reflection. it is the only time my mind is quiet and undistracted.
.
throughout the day i have to continually look to god first and know in faith that the rest will follow.
.
 it will be a lifetime of perfecting this practice so that it is ingrained in my very being. it is the first step to recovery and i am on my way!
.
i pray that you will be encouraged today. we are all  #hisworkinprogress !🦋
.
.
.
w/love
.
.
.

text:
consent has nothing to do with clothing! .

consistently victims of sexual assault are being let down. 
victims of sexual assaults are often asked what they did/said/wore to provoke an attack. 
as a society we are being told what we should do to prevent attacks rather than telling those committing the crime not to do it in the first place. .

what a person is or is not wearing does not give anyone the right to take advantage. 
using a person's clothing choice against them the justify rape is appalling. 
for people to fear attacks, not just because of the act itself, but because having no express desire for sexual activity will be disregarded due something as simple as your knickers, is disgusting .

i pick my clothing for me.
i pick my underwear because it makes me feel cute.
i dress in what is comfortable / clean.
some days i wear a plunging neckline.
some a turtle neck.
i wear yoga pants.
i wear slacks.
i dress to suit me.
i do not dress to be sexually assaulted! .

no one does! .

#thisisnotconsent #itsnotokay
#consentissexy #nomeansno #teachthemyoung #ibelieveher #ibelieveyou #metoo

text:
"i never had a reason to separate junot diaz from his art. in fact, so much of what made his art so true and so compelling was how much of him existed within it.  but much like my relationship with kanye’s work, continuing to show appreciation for it means questioning my morals."
this is an excerpt from a piece i wrote earlier this year titled, "when our heroes fail us" (link in bio).
-
back in may, news broke that pulitzer prize-winning author junot diaz had forcibly kissed a young female writer. he'd also displayed other forms of misogynistic behavior.  he's one of my literary heroes, and that disturbing news forced me to reconcile junot diaz the person with junot diaz the author. -
this week, the pulitzer board announced that diaz could remain a member after their investigation showed no evidence of wrongdoing. while i'm glad that he hasn't completely sabotaged his literary legacy, i have conflicted feelings. are we just supposed to pretend that these past incidents didn't happen? in this era of #metoo, how do we move forward when the accused is welcomed back into public favor?  how do you feel?
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
revisiting my top 10: drive 
pt. 2/2
spoilers

another element i forgot and was delighted by was the aggressive use of fade transitions. scenes bleed into one another, giving us the feeling of a fugue state. it’s as if we’re reeling in gosling’s pov right alongside him in the driver’s seat (pun intended). gosling is an antihero, but he’s distant from the criminals he drives and only kills and/or intimidates those who attack first. however...his true darkness surfaces when he slaps christina hendricks, pins her down, covers her mouth, and threatens to kill her. it’s even more visceral  in the #metoo age. the act is a domestic terror we can relate to more than a curtain rod through a baddie’s gullet. it borders on exploitation; willing to take the hero to a savage place that would definitely not be included today. 
there’s so much more to talk about. the orange/blue color palette. the framing. the allegorical motifs. the la setting. the driving scenes. the visceral yet sparse violence. ughhhsogood. 
overall, drive is mesmerizing, enchanting, and brutal. though he’d gleefully polarize people with his next film, refn held the keys to everybody’s hearts and eyes in 2011, and forever changed the way i appreciate cinema. 
next up: moonlight

text:
i had the immense honor of seeing tarana burke speak a few weeks ago. she is the founder of the #metoo movement and has been working with victims of abuse for over 25 years.  when i tell you that woman knows her shit— she knows her shit. she’s been in the trenches working to end sexual violence and abuse for years.
.
.
one of the things that most struck me was what she said about how to talk to people who are sharing their abuse with you— she said the most powerful and healing thing you can say to them is “i believe you”. that you can create decades of healing with that one phrase.
.
.
it got me thinking of all kinds of abuse — not only sexual abuse. and how often when people share their abuse what they get instead is an intellectual nit picking. “are you sure that happened?” “well that didn’t happen to me” “i think you must be misinterpreting the situation—i doubt they would behave that way” “i don’t believe everyone in the family is thinking or saying that to you”.
.
.
abuse is not something to pick apart like a mathematical problem. it is a severely traumatizing event for a person. it is vulnerable enough for them to share it with you. when you then ask questions like the above you cannot even begin to understand the violence you perpetuate in that person’s heart and body all over again.  you drag up years of being told to be quiet and invalidated which allowed their abuse to continue. and when you ask someone sharing their abuse with you those q’s you are recreating the experience of all the gaslighting they ever received when they tried to share they were being abused. you are essentially unconsciously participating in gaslighting and abusive behavior yourself when you talk to someone this way who is sharing about their abuse with you.  it is energetically violent to make someone’s abuse sharing experience about “opinions that differ” or telling them they may not be accurate in their experience. you are silencing them. often this creates the feeling of being abused all over again for them.  please don’t accidentally perpetuate abuse by doing this.
.
.
listen. seek to understand where they are coming from. tell them “i believe you”. that is caring.

text:
thursday, december 06, 2018
4:00pm to 6:00pm “revolutionary dreams and haitian girlhood"

régine michelle jean-charles is a black feminist literary scholar and cultural critic specializing in francophone studies. her scholarship and teaching on world literatures in french includes work on black france, sub-saharan africa, haiti and the haitian diaspora. she is currently associate professor of romance languages and literatures and african and african diaspora studies at boston college. she holds a ba from the university of pennsylvania in french and african and african diaspora studies, and an am and phd in romance languages and literatures from harvard university.  she has received fellowships from the ford foundation, the mellon mays foundation and the woodrow wilson foundation.
her first book, conflict bodies:  the politics of rape representation in the francophone imaginary (columbus: ohio state university press, 2014) examines theoretical, visual, and literary texts that challenge the dominant views of sexual violence.  she has authored numerous scholarly articles that have appeared in edited volumes and peer-reviewed journals such as the journal of haitian studies, american quarterly, callaloo, french forum, journal of romance studies, research in african literatures, and small axe. her current research focuses on girlhood in contemporary haitian literature and visual culture. professor jean-charles serves as a board member of a long walk home, inc., a non-profit organization that uses art to educate, inspire, and mobilize young people to end violence against girls and women. she is also a regular contributor to media outlets like wgbh and cognoscenti, where she has weighed in on topics ranging from #metoo to issues affecting the haitian diaspora.

text:
this is my #metoo post, i've posted about this before, but not in much detail. 
today i had a phone call, it was the denver district attorney's office. i was informed my rapist is asking the judge that he not have to register as a sex offender anymore, since "he's had good behavior and done everything right". i learned a lot about my rapist today that i never knew, after the incident i was never told anything about what transpired in court, if he had been sentenced, nothing. i never had closure. i didn't how old he was, i either didn't know,  or had mentally blocked out his name, i only knew him by his nicknames "billy" or "snake", i hate that i was reminded, because now i feel completely screwed up and sick  inside. today i learned more about him than i cared to know. i guess i get to have an opinion about his request to the judge.  of course i don't feel comfortable with him not registering, no i dont think he should be allowed to not register. i don't even like the idea that he's still alive, that he was allowed medical care in prison to maintain his hiv, why not just let him fucking die?  why do prisoners get special treatment?  i had to get tested often before i was 18 to make sure i didn't contract that shit.  he drugged my cup of water, and eventually attacked me in a parking garage stairwell, (indoor closed stairwell). it was the last time i prayed to god, begged him outloud to make him stop, as he was over me telling me "oh you think your god is good?  that he will save you? i always wanted a young girl to love and now i'm fucking one" do you think he should be allowed not to register judge?  he doesnt look like how i remember,  he's obviously had his face smashed up during his time in prison. good i hope it was agonizing.  there are rapists everywhere,  watch your children and keep them close. for my colorado friends. this is his face. he may be your neighbor? he was released 5 years ago,  i had no idea!
#metoo #survivor  #sexoffendercolorado #sexoffender

•

•

•

text:
writing your story...
i’m writing my story so that young women aren’t afraid to explain to their children what lives they lived..
whether it be by choice or coincidence, 
i chose 3 years ago to start documenting my story to tell to you.
my child,
my miniature me,
to show you my rights from my wrongs,
& they’re listed literally within these nina simone songs,
my little me,
y o u..
i love you but i refuse to give to you what was given to me.
i will let you live your own legacy & write along these pages with me.
my baby nyi’el...
i look forward to crying like how i’ve already cried these past 5 years of your existence..
weeping,
on how i need to break this generational curse,
and to you...
i owe you that much.
your legacy is now being created for you to live on... 🖤
tattoo cover up mua ::. @iamlee__ 📸 ::. @vitalyny •
•

text:
i never thought, in my life, i would be part of the #metoo movement. i never thought i would be a survivor of rape. actually, to be honest that was my biggest fear. to get raped. i remember thinking, when i was younger, that if i got raped i would die.then my biggest fear came true...but i didn't die.

sometimes i've felt like i was gonna die. because the pain and confusion was so heavy and consuming.

i know what it feels like to think that i'm not gonna make it. to not care if i recover or not. or even think that i have a good future ahead of me. thank god i made it through those years. i am not a victim or defined by what happened to me. and neither are you. surviving and thriving after rape is possible. notice i didnt say "easy" but possible.

believe in that possible.

still a queen 👑✊.
.
.
.

text:
cw: sexual assault, verbal abuse. ⠀
⠀
these past few months i’ve been appalled at how sexual assault and abuse has been discussed in the media and even amongst friends and family. i find myself in conversations thinking, do they know it happened to me too? would they be saying this right now if they knew it did? sometimes i share that i’m a survivor, if i’m feeling brave. other times i sit in silence looking for an out so that i don’t collapse into a puddle of panic. ⠀
⠀
i’ve spent the last two years in therapy sifting through how abuse and assault have effected my life. i’ve realized that these experiences landed me in a position of using and abusing my own body. my body has felt like a battle field for so long, and finally in this last year or so i think i’ve found peace… ⠀
⠀
until these last few months when my attempts to block out related media weren’t working anymore because the stories just hit too close to home. and then my body became a war zone again… ⠀
⠀
“she’s just saying these things for attention” - shots fired⠀
“was she drinking?” - crumbling walls⠀
“she deserved it” - bombs erupting throughout my body⠀
⠀
did that mean i deserved it too? does that mean if i’m honest about what happened that its just for attention? does this mean that every drunken night full of screaming and verbal abuse was my fault? i’ve been struggling in this body again, and while i won’t blame anyone, i will say these comments are only helping to fuel the flames and give ammunition to my inner enemies. my body feels used and abused all over again every time i hear someone blame or ridicule a survivor. ⠀
⠀
this post is to share a small glimpse of my story so that someone might rethink the next comments they make about assault or abuse. this post is for the person that needs to know they’re not alone. this post is not meant for action persay but rather a post for visibility and authenticity. because i believe these are the only ways we will make progress and build understanding. so i ask you merely to think, just think before you make a comment about assault or abuse that may be harmful. think before you add fuel to the fire of anothers war zone⠀
#metoo #believesurvivors

text:
this is not my typical post.. taken on my phone. out of focus. and i did nothing to make this pretty. i personally didn't want to make this photo pretty. there is nothing pretty about it. 
i have struggled with whether i should share my #metoo experience for a long time. what good would it do? there will be backlash, and criticism i'm sure. my family will find out. and so far, i've told no one but ethan. however, this is a subject i am passionate about. and today, i had a conversation with someone who said "..my point was that we still realize the life we are part of such as there are neighborhoods i will not walk at night alone due to the danger... it is still my right but may not be safe. i know that if i got mugged people would blame me for walking in an area that this would happen at night. 
it is their fault and i would be the victim but i would think twice walking there again or what i would carry. prudence.." this was about wether a woman is truly asking for it when she walks around half naked. 
well. here is a small part of my story. this is what i was wearing the last time i was raped. mostly anyway. the same pair of jeans. except my drug rug what black and white. and i was wearing a hat.  the boy was older than me. taller than me. raised in a christian home and being trained for the air force. i had known him for months. i considered him a friend and trusted him. and i remember that night in all of it's terrible vivid detail. and with as hard as this is to put out there.. i'm going to. i was with one of my closest friends and a few others. and we we're drinking.. and when she left, he kissed me on the mouth. i backed away.. i didn't like it. he asked me to have sex. i said no. i said i wasn't comfortable with it. any girl who has ever been to a party knows that this then becomes the mans perogative to convince you. he continued to ask. to hang on me. i continued to say no. over. and over. at which point he picked me up and threw me on his bed. i pretended i was so drunk i passed out. and as i lay there hypersensitive to every fucking sense that i had he sat next to me and put his hand on my waist. he tried to kiss me. continued in comments.

text:
so i’ve been mia because i was selected to be a juror last week... in a child sexual abuse case. needless to say i saw every right to drop off the face of the world and drink... heavily. .

i was intrigued by the process. it was something i’d been curious about... what’s the process? how do they decide jurors ... how close is this to an episode of #suits or #lawandorder ? but the gravity set in quickly as i learned i was one of 12 out of 80 to be selected... well really our county holds 1/2 mil people sooo my odds were slim. . 
the case is done now so i can talk about it (thank god). as i learned of the details of the case i was struck by the severity of realizing i was going to be responsible for deciding who was “at fault”... an 8year old girl (now 12 testifying on the stand and who the defense is saying she lying ... bc.. children lie and want attention) or a 50 something year old man who by our legal standards innocent until proven guilty. i tried to put people i love in those seats to understand the decision in front of me. .
i drank every night. i cried every night. and even after the case has been done i went to yoga and cried as i sent my practice out to the girls who testified. .
i learned from one person who testified that she has interviewed 4k little girls in cases like these... 4,000k. i’ve ran over the details of the case far too many times in my mind, i’ve called my momma ruing , and woken from nightmares.
.
even still... i find myself trying to practice gratitude in this coming week that this case was put in my hands to follow my intuition, my heart, and the facts that’s the prosecution did their job to prove this man guilty. may these girls find peace, justice, and solitude in their lives and may the weight i now  carry lessen theirs. .
#juryduty #thejuror #themtoo #metoo #denvercolorado #sadnessabound #tooyoung #troubled #heavy #justice #juror #disclosure #strength #watchoutforyourchildren #children #therightchoice #guilty

text:
/頭好痛又一直哭，這是正常的能量釋放吧/
因為公投的關係許多小時被性侵過的受害者會在網路上分享童年的創傷，希望呼籲大家性平教育的重要性
殊不知，這帶來的衝擊那麼那麼大。
每看一次案例就逼得我們再面對一次自己的傷口
不是痊癒了而是藏起來了
就算再久都會突然想起而隱隱作痛
或許藉由這次的社會運動也是讓我們學習面對自己
答應你，答應我，我們都會好好的。

在臉書貼出文章後更發現很多人都有一樣的創傷互相感到心疼 ———————————
“我支持婚姻平權啊，但覺得性教育太早教了”
請問，是要等到小孩被性侵害的時候才要教嗎
你知道有多少人在童年時被性侵過嗎
嗯，我想你不知道，因為你很幸運
但我就沒那麼幸運了

常常很多人問我為什麼那麼努力宣傳這次的公投
因為
我常在想，如果小時候發生事情的時候我知道如何處理就好了

可是一個小學二年級的小孩根本不知道怎麼處理
因為沒有人教

我能同理到許多人的情緒
因為我自己經歷過
《分裂》這部電影裡，男主角變成野獸之後說：不純潔的人是指沒受過苦的、沒被染指的、沒被火燒的。所以他認為小時被性侵過的女主角是純潔的，最後放她一條生路，這在我看來就是一種同理心⋯⋯ 我也不知為何最近這件事會一直浮上我心頭，雖然過了很久很久，身體的傷好像一直會記著，當時的驚嚇也會記著

但好險
從小就學會找宣洩的出口
該面對自己的時候就要面對
雖然真的很痛很痛很痛
現在可能藉由去做某些事來幫自己療癒
例如
幫忙這次公投過關、保護其他孩子不要受到侵害、讓大家學會保護自己

喔對了
如果你看到文章也認識我媽
千萬不要跟她說
我不想讓她難過

#回家投票吧
#不管結果如何我們都要好好的
➡️公投案號14,15兩個同意
➡️第10,11,12三個不同意讓幸福ok
#metoo
hashtags: #回家投票吧, #不管結果如何我們都要好好的, #metoo

人から、自身の被害を「乗り越えられた？」と聞かれることがある。「乗り越えることではなく、毎日、これと生きていかなければならない」

最後に、被害に苦しむ人々へ言葉を送った。「傷は自分が一番、よく知っている。自らの真実を信じてほしい。どんなに周りが否定しても、あなたは悪くない」

- how drunk someone is
- if they flirted
- if they danced with you - they're silence - what they were wearing, even underwear! ➖

and then people wonder why victims don't come forward... to relive that trauma, be blamed and have the perpetrator walk away. i'm sorry to that young girl.

text:
to amanda kelly, 
global news and all montrealers. 
mom lied!! false allegations and perjury is a criminal offence.

mom did this knowing i would be detained in prison so that she could run off with my daughter.

she has done the same to the two previous fathers of her children.

i was never convicted. i got out of prison only to search for my daughter who is in danger with that woman.

my daughter was located in toronto and has inflicted harm. her half brother was sent to a children's hospital in toronto where mom was hiding under a different name. 
i have the right to defend myself and expose this madness that the laval police department intentionally neglected to investigate even after i've been begging them for help years before mom's lies.

there are no other victims, it never happened. the only victim is my daughter.

i was a great father to this little girl. she was happy here with me. mom needed to get rid of me and leave the province with my daughter. 
this case is now in two different provinces in family courts, criminal courts and civil court procedures. 
here is the link to the fake news article that was printed on me. october 28, 2014 (posted below). i strongly suggest the journalist that printed that without doing any research of his/her own to take it down. 
mom is going to jail. 
remember my words. 
children have been hurt and families destroyed by one woman's lies and violence. it took her two minuets to make a call and do all this damage but it's taking me over four years to be heard. see the difference? 
signed...stephanos chrysanthe svourenos

text:
every witch practices with their own code of ethics, just like everyone else. we all have good and bad in us, darkness and light. the most powerful witches i met know that you need to acknowledge both sides of yourself and your experiences, finding balance. ⚔️ some witches refuse to work magick on others, some only do so with consent, some only for justice. i met witches who hex serial rapists, seeking recourse where our patriarchal criminal justice system - designed to benefit men - continues to fail women. others will use their powers however they want. every witch has their reasons behind their ethical approach. 
witchcraft ethics are rooted in a belief in what’s called the three fold law, which states that any energy you put out into the world will come back on you tenfold. magickal karma, if you will. 🌀not all witches believe in the law, but those who do often do so because they’ve learned the hard way. hex someone or practice powerful dark magic, and it’ll result in chronic illness, job loss, your house burning down, or the death of a loved one. not today, not tomorrow, but it’ll catch up to you eventually. 
witch or not, if we all acted in respect of the three fold law, we would be a hell of a lot nicer to one another. because “a hex always comes for its pound of flesh,” as one witch told me. unless you don’t believe in the law. 😉

photo taken at a ritual hex on supreme court justice brett kavanaugh at @catlandbooks. witches gathered to hex him, trump, and mitch mcconnell using these poppets. poppets are dolls used as proxies for the spell’s targets as is common in conjure, voodoo, hoodoo, vodou, and other witchcraft practices common to the south. after the ritual hex, the witches held a second ritual to honor survivors of sexual assault (nearly everyone in the room, myself included). because as we’ve learned in the #metoo movement, justice is a  necessary element of healing. ✊🏼 shot for my ongoing project on the intersectionality of contemporary witchcraft. more in bio.

text:
words cannot express how devastated i am and hundreds more are about the recent sexual assault and rape case in ireland. 
a 17 year old girl was allegedly raped in ireland, but has since committed suicide since her trial. during the trial, the defence lawyer told the jury, “you have to look at the way she was dressed. she was wearing a thong with a lace front." never should someone be raped or sexually assaulted because of the clothes they wear. this is unacceptable behaviour from the man who allegedly raped her and his defence team. because of this a smart, kind, and exceptional girl lost her life. 
how many more girls have to be sexually assaulted and raped before these terrible people stop? 
#thisisnotconsent #timesup #metoo #wewantavoice #wewillbeheard #timesneedtochange #nomorebs
name: Girls Will Change The World

text: •⚖️• v e n u s •🐍• planet of feminine charm, venus spends the rest of the year in libra and scorpio. ✨ the planet that guides our sense of pleasure, what we like, what we enjoy, venus has completed her retrograde and is now free to progress.... ✨ what have we learned during the retrograde spin cycle? ✨ plenty. ✨ the emphasis on scorpio themes in 2018 has dug up very-many issues - particularly around women’s sexuality and power dynamics. ✨ libra brings a sense of fairness, balance and equilibrium into play, smoothing out some of the crumpled, creases and stains of scorpio’s reign. ✨ i’ve now a certainty in my bones we’ve still so far to go... ✨✨✨✨✨🖤✨✨✨✨✨ throughout the remainder of the year we’ve opportunities to doggedly implement the growth we’ve achieved through jupiter in scorpio - if you’ve recognised an imbalance of power now is the time to uphold your values!!! ✨🖤✨ hold them tight ✨🖤✨ i just saw a really tacky sexist advert called out on the news, as it says ‘fancy’ women’s underwear is a ‘must have’ for the holidays...✨ it’s getting a backlash from feminist groups but reading the comments is proof how deep denial runs...✨ you might have also read about the court case where a woman’s underwear was used against her in a rape trial. ✨ women’s underwear, venus-libra-scorpio. fashion as a means for disempowerment, venus-libra-scorpio. sexual harassment trials with clothing, venus-libra-scorpio. ✨ let’s not forget the point of this year, of dr ford, of turfing the snakes out of their dark hiding spaces - the point is to feel good about what we choose to wear, to feel empowered in our sense of self. to feel confident, beautiful and safe. to have faith that we’ll be believed, if only by the ones that truly matter. ✨🙏🏼 still a long way to go but stand strong throughout the rest of 2018 - it’s not over 🖤 #metoo #venusinscorpio #venusinlibra #venus #venusretrograde #balance #justice #goddess #equilibrium #asabovesobelow #astrologysigns #venusaphrodite #scorpioseason #horoscope #horoscopes #starsignstyle pic discovered via @theauriclife ⚖️🙏🏼 #thefashionastrologer

text:
the time i didn’t have a plan.
.
.
i’ve heard people say life is like playing chest, not checkers...and i’m not really sure what that means.  my guess is that they’re referring to being several steps ahead of the next person...strategically planning your end from the beginning...like winning is planned, intentional, and made from hard work.  and i agree with that to some extent but these days i’m starting to wonder.
.
.
i’ve been working on this #imabeautifulmess album and tbh i’m not really sure i gotta plan, or an expectation of an outcome.  there’s no clever strategy, no market scheme, and believe me...i’m not several steps ahead of anybody.  i got some songs i wrote, a guitar, and some live recorded takes...some of them rough and some of them surprisingly brilliant...but all of them are very much like life...real.  and i guess that’s what i hope people get from it and what i hope they take from it.
.
.
maybe life isn’t like chess at all, because i don’t feel like i know my next several moves...i only know my next move.  and maybe that’s enough until i know the next one.  maybe it’s ok that i don’t have this plan or creative hook or brilliant scheme to get people to listen or even like my music and i think that’s what probably makes it so dope.  because whether it turns out good, bad, rough or even surprisingly brilliant...it will all be real.  and maybe that’s no so bad after all. 💜✍🏾💯
.
.
✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨

.
.
.
.

pre_proc_tweet:
the time i didn’t have a plan.
.
.
i’ve heard people say life is like playing chest, not checkers...and i’m not really sure what that means.  my guess is that they’re referring to being several steps ahead of the next person...strategically planning your end from the beginning...like winning is planned, intentional, and made from hard work.  and i agree with that to some extent but these days i’m staing to wonder.
.
.
i’ve been working on this  album and tbh i’m not really sure i gotta plan, or an expectation of an outcome.  there’s no clever strategy, no market scheme, and believe me...i’m not several steps ahead of anybody.  i got some songs i wrote, a guitar, and some live recorded takes...some of them rough and some of them surprisingly brilliant...but all of them are very much like life...real.  and i guess that’s what i hope people get from it and what i hope they take from it.
.
.
maybe life isn’t like chess at all, because i don’t feel like i know my next several moves...i only know my next move.  and maybe that’s enough until i know the next one.  maybe it’s ok that i don’t have this plan or creative hook or brilliant scheme to get people to listen or even like my music and i think that’s what probably makes it so dope.  because whether it turns out good, bad, rough or even surprisingly brilliant...it will all be real.  and maybe that’s no so bad after all. 💜✍🏾💯
.
.
✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨

.
.
.
.

text:
our first ‘women for change run/walk’ was initiated as an ad-hoc event and a direct reaction to the dramatic events unfolding in march 2016. 
within one week cape town was shocked by the brutal murders of several teen girls across the city. as the largest all-women running community we had to take a stand to protest the violence against women and children in south africa.

looking back, it hasn't changed much. everyday we have children and women being attacked, raped and murdered.  abuse against women and children is an epidemic in this country. something we have to overcome now! 
let's unite and stand as one to protect our wonderful children and women. let's keep on claiming our public spaces back. let's continue to spread love, because together we are the change. let's do it now! 
stand with us united in sandton city on the 1st december during 16 days of activism. 
#womenforchange #sisterhood #together #metoo #16daysofactivism #timesup #women #thetotalshutdown #spreadlove #changetheworld #girlpower

text:
our first ‘women for change run/walk’ was initiated as an ad-hoc event and a direct reaction to the dramatic events unfolding in march 2016. 
within one week cape town was shocked by the brutal murders of several teen girls across the city. as the largest all-women running community we had to take a stand to protest the violence against women and children in south africa.

looking back, it hasn't changed much. everyday we have children and women being attacked, raped and murdered.  abuse against women and children is an epidemic in this country. something we have to overcome now! 
let's unite and stand as one to protect our wonderful children and women. let's keep on claiming our public spaces back. let's continue to spread love, because together we are the change. let's do it now! 
stand with us united in sandton city on the 1st december during 16 days of activism. 
#womenforchange #sisterhood #together #metoo #16daysofactivism #timesup #women #thetotalshutdown #spreadlove #changetheworld #girlpower

text: my heart has stopped three times in the modern history of fashion. the first, alexander mcqueen’s live painted dress s/s 1999. the second, miuccia prada’s floral heels f/w 2008. the third, this #handsoff puffer jacket by @katewalz for @querenciastudio. kate, with all the modesty in her character, always lights up with charismatic enthusiasm when she speaks to me about her design. an ingenious interpretation of the #metoo movement, this scarlet jacket represents not only a revolution in the fashion industry but also a shift in our social paradigm. it’s about time for some solid green action rather than mere green washing. take this walz. you won’t regret it. follow @pildora.nyc for the full story.❤️

text:
people always want to know how to stay sober and for me it's all about incorporating wellness proactively to keep my energy at a high vibration. when i am balanced in mind, body and spirit i have no desire to drink or binge on sugary treats. 
i keep track of it all by using my daily wellness tool that my brother and i created. 
the outside pentagon represents the five core pillars that we realized kept us hydrated, well rested and helped us lose weight! they are all free and anyone can do them everyday for wellness 
the inside triangle are personal preference extra credits for achieving goals. for general balance do one thing everyday for mind body and spirit.  for body transformation do three things for your body like yoga, hiking or a boxing class. i also used it for debt pay off and career growth 💰
this little system is shockingly effective when done everyday and helps me focus on small daily change!

#godry #drydiet #godry #healthyandwealthy #meditation #simplicityeverywhere #soberissexy #soberyogi #transformation #empoweringwomen #nohangover #noalcohol #metoo #mentalhealth #teetotaler

टेलीविज़न की दुनिया के साथ-साथ बड़े पर्दे के सबसे 'संस्कारी बाबूजी' आलोक नाथ की मुश्किलें अब बढ़ सकती हैं। मुंबई पुलिस ने टीवी अभिनेता आलोक नाथ के खिलाफ बलात्कार का मामला दर्ज कर लिया है। ओशिवारा पुलिस स्टेशन में यह मामला दर्ज किया गया है। मीटू मूवमेंट के तहत टेलीविजन लेखिका विनता नंदा ने बीते दिनों एक्टर आलोक नाथ पर यौन उत्पीड़न का आरोप लगाया था। इसके बाद कई और अभिनेत्रियों ने  ##metoo #आलोकनाथ #यौनउत्पीड़न #यौनदुर्व्यवहार #संस्कारीबाबूजी

text:
[ l dans ville ] #3 • organisée par un collectif d'associations pour que le mouvement #metoo soit suivi d'actions, #noustoutes se veut être une déferlante féministe. un électrochoc humaniste. ⚡️ marie darrieussecq et annie ernaux, isabelle carré, karine viard, philippe torreton, catherine ringer, jeanne chehral et arthur h ou encore rockaya diallo, guillaume meurisse, lauren bastide…autant de noms qui vous sont familiers. autant de personnes qui ont signé, avec près de 250 autres, une tribune publiée ce 19 novembre dans mediapart et sur france inter. ils et elles appellent dans leur texte à marcher contre les violences sexistes et sexuelles dont sont victimes de trop nombreuses femmes en france et dans le monde. « les violences sexistes et sexuelles empêchent plus de la moitié de l’humanité, les femmes et les filles, d’exercer leurs droits fondamentaux. elles bouleversent leur vie entière.
les solutions sont connues. elles sont portées de longue date par les associations qui accueillent, avec des moyens dérisoires, des femmes victimes partout en france. nous avons besoin de politiques publiques ambitieuses de prévention qui pourraient changer les comportements, comme elles l’ont fait pour des sujets de santé publique. nous avons besoin d’une éducation obligatoire dès le plus jeune âge à la non-violence et à l’égalité filles-garçons, d’une formation systématique des professionnel·les qui accueillent les victimes, de l’utilisation effective des outils de protection prévus par la loi, de l’augmentation significative des moyens alloués aux associations et de places suffisantes pour l’hébergement des femmes victimes. » ⚡️la manifestation, sous le mot d’ordre #noustoutes, est prévue le samedi 24 novembre 2018. ⚡️ vous pouvez rejoindre le mouvement. une carte annonce les différents rassemblements dans toute la france sur la page fb #noustoutes.  a paris, rdv à 14 heures, place de la madeleine ! •
#lesambitieuses #borntobeambitious #ambition  #womenwithambition #ambitionquotes #femmes #hommes#women #men #ambassadrices #ambassadors #ville #city#society#société #initiatives #initiativesforchange #france #noustoutes #orangetheworld

text:
some sample of the 16 step program i'm starting with battered womens social services. some great reminders and tools for boundary setting, interpersonal effectiveness, emotional regulation & validation, healthy relationships etc. this program was apparently started as an alternative to aa(which is patriarchal/religious in inception so could not serve more diverse circumstances). 16 step isn't just for addiction therapy; i'm personally trying it to debunk my own social stigmas, family scripts, etc that i was conditioned with that no longer service me. i will soon post slides from a related helpful training program at my union in regards to the #metoo movement awareness. don't feel guilty or ashamed for doing the work on yourself; the most important investment of your thriving life.  hope it helps y'all and ur loved ones navigate better communication and self-preservation :) * hugs🚀🛸🛎🔥⚡🌈☄♨️🎯⛳🥅⬆️🔙🔛🔝🔜💯❇❗ sincerely,
p

text:
this can happen all too easily. with our partners, with our children. we care so much we forget to put ourselves first.

and without oxygen we're all fucked lol.

dont ever lose yourself.

text_retweet:
#repost @pallavi_006 with @make_repost
・・・
#inktober day 5 : #stories #whenwomensupport
when women support each other incredible things happen. ✨
one of the things i find most inspiring is women openly supporting and lifting each other up. the righteous woman has a basic belief, that women should have each other’s backs, no matter what. 
#metoo - to all the girls out there who have gone through any kind of pain because of sexual harassment or assault, we are there for you, we might not feel your pain but we are there to back you up, to support you, to listen to you, to believe you. to everyone i know, if you need a ear, i am there to listen. support each other during this tough time, be the ear for someone whose suffering, tell them they can count on you, hold their hands and help them move forward. 
it’s just sad the world we are living in, we may not be able to change the world, but we can reduce the suffering of one another by being there. share your stories with people you trust, it might not cure the pain but it will help you heal faster.
image reference - @pinterest .
.
.

2/3 that is a wrap of ngtby. we were filming in a black box studio with minimal set design representing a location with different trailers where the characters were living. in that aspect, it was quite similar to dogville. however, our set was more minimalistic and the lighting was the key to set time of the day, emotions or abstract moments. this, along the fact we had to film more than 50 minutes in 4 days, made the shoot super intense and challenging.

thank you again to my amazing camera and lighting people. you are stars! :d

text:
on @popcultureconfidential; tonia sina, intimacy director ‘directing sex scenes for stage and film in the #metoo era’
when hbo and david simon hired an intimacy coordinator/director to choreograph and monitor the on-set sex scenes on his show ‘the deuce’ it started a lot of interesting conversations. i wanted to know more!

on the show this week, one of the co-founders of ‘intimacy directors international’, executive director tonia sina. we talk about what intimacy director does, acts as an advocate for the actors, keeping actors physically and psychologically safe when acting in scenes of an intimate nature. as stunt coordinators have long done for fight scenes.

text:
broadly speaking, there are three core elements to #metoo, writes cristy clark:

1. the sheer volume of disclosures highlights that sexual harassment and abuse are unacceptably widespread – and that institutions and society at large are failing to protect and support victims. 
2. the practice of using the hashtag to challenge the stigma and shame that has somehow accompanied identifying as a victim. 
3. the fact some disclosures on twitter have sought to name and shame perpetrators of abuse in order to seek accountability and justice.
.
read more here: 
https://theconversation.com/metoo-exposes-legal-failures-but-trial-by-twitter-isnt-one-of-them-92683

text_retweet:
melena @takebooks hat nicht nur ein hammer-foto gemacht mit glück dich! guckt auch unbedingt auf ihrem feed (und folgt ihr ☝🏼☝🏼☝🏼☝🏼 - heute hat sie auch eine besondere insta-story 😉)
vor allem greift sie in ihrem post ein sehr wichtiges thema aus glück dich! auf. welche erfahrungen habt ihr dazu gemacht? ich dachte lang, ich bin allein damit, aber nein. umso erschreckender, dass es so viele betrifft, die aus scham schweigen und dieses schweigen nur denen nutzt, die sich falsch verhalten 😤#repost @takebooks with @get_repost
・・・
habt ihr schon mal erfahrungen mit (sexueller) belästigung gemacht?
°
werbung i rezensionsexemplar
°
spätestens seit der #metoo debatte, ist dieses thema allgegenwärtig.
auch das buch von @monikapfundmeier beschäftigt sich mit dem thema.
darf mein chef mir gegenüber dauernd anzügliche witze machen und mich dinge fragen die in meine privatsphäre dringen?
muss ich mir das gefallen lassen? oder stell ich mich einfach nur an und bin verklemmt?
°
nein! egal was für eine bemerkung es ist, egal was für ein spruch. selbst wenn andere das als nicht schlimm empfinden würden, darfst du selbst über deine eigene grenze entscheiden und diese auch deutlich machen. niemand darf über deine grenze gehen, egal ob es freunde, bekannte, fremde oder auch dein chef sind. du bestimmst über dich selbst, deine emotionen und dein leben. sag stopp! °
habe ich schon mal erfahrungen damit gemacht?
ja. ich denke fast jede frau wurde schon mal auf eine art angesprochen, die für sie nicht okay war. aber ich kenne meine grenze und mache diese auch deutlich. und ich hoffe ihr da draußen auch. 
und lasst euch davon nicht abbringen, denn nur ihr entscheidet wo diese sich befindet und nicht andere! °
falls ihr wissen wollt, was die protagonistin nora für eine erfahrung gemacht hat, dann schaut euch das buch von @monikapfundmeier an. gerade gibt es das als ebook für 2,99€😱
ich habe es schon gelesen und meine meinung dazu gibt es morgen auf meinem blog ❤️ #mainwunder #glückdich #bookstagram #bücherliebe #bibliophile #booklover #loveyourself #supporther #femalepower #metoo #buch #monikapfundmeier #diy #goyourownway #liveyourlove #lesen #buch 
@ninablogaholic @mainwunder

text: • ⚖️ • v e n u s • • • planet e hijeshi femërore, venusi kalon pjesën tjetër të vitit në shenjën e peshores dhe akrepit. ✨ planeti që udhëzon ndjenjën e kënaqësisë, atë që ne dëshirojmë, atë që ne gëzojmë, venusi e ka përfunduar fazën e tij dhe tani është i lirë të përparojë ... ✨ ✨ peshorja sjell një ndjenjë të drejtë, ekuilibër dhe duke zbutur disa nga rrudhat, copëzat dhe njollat ​​e sundimit të akrepit. 🖤✨✨✨✨✨ gjatë pjesës së mbetur të vitit kemi mundësi të zbatojmë me forcë rritjen që kemi bërë arritur përmes jupiterit në akrep- nëse e keni njohur një çekuilibër të pushtetit tani është koha për të mbështetur vlerat tuaja !!! ✨🖤✨ mbajini ato të shtrënguara ✨🖤- qëllimi është të ndihemi mirë në atë që zgjedhim të vëmë, të ndjehemi të fuqizuar në sensin tonë. të ndjehemi të sigurt, të bukur. ende një rrugë e gjatë për të bërë, por qēndroni të fortë gjatë pjesës tjetër të vitit 2018 - nuk ka mbaruar 🖤 #metoo #venusinscorpio #venusinlibra #venus #venusretrograde #balance #horoskopi #horoscope #venusnepeshore #venusneakrep

text:
cw: sexual violence, army / military brutality

instances of sexual violence live on in cultural memory in different ways. in 'the last song' temsula ao writes the story of apenyo, a young naga woman who was subjected to gang-rape and murdered, along with her mother, by the indian army. in the story, the army decides to visit the village and arrest all leaders for their 'crime' of paying taxes to underground forces —something the villagers were compelled to do. incensed by apenyo and the villagers' defiance the soldiers shoot, kick and club those trying to escape or seek shelter in the old church. the captain who leads the rapes sees villagers trying help the two women, and orders soldiers to surround the church and empty their guns into it, after which it is set on fire. the new church too, along with granaries and houses catch the blaze. the villagers are threatened not to spread the news of what had happened there.

afterwards, as the villagers recoup their losses, it is decided after much debate that as per old traditions, deaths from 'unnatural' causes could not be buried in the village graveyard. as a compromise mother and daughter are buried just outside the boundary of the graveyard to show that their fellow villagers had not abandoned them. but no headstones are erected. the story ends with the two gravesites as unmarked grassy knolls whose story lives on in the souls of those who survived the darkest day of the village some thirty odd years ago.

apenyo is a fictional stand-in for real women affected by army #impunity in areas such as the #northeast affected by #afspa.

what do you make of apenyo's actions and how do you respond to her story? what can resistance or '#justice' look like in these complex situations? what are some stories of resistance that you have heard?

#zubaanbooks #exitimpunity #sexualviolence #endsexualviolence #metoo #metooindia #smashbrahminicalpatriarchy #feminist #feministart #womensrights #feministpractice #genderbasedviolence #resistance #racism

text:
“in the end anti-black, anti-female, and all forms of discrimination are equivalent to the same thing: anti-humanism.” - shirley chisholm

have you seen “chisholm ‘72: unbought & unbossed” (2004) directed/produced by shola lynch yet? 
i was able to view the film in its entirety for the first time at the ✨”mosaic literary conference: #metoo” by @mosaicmagazine✨at the bronx museum @bronxmuseum 
this film recounts chisholm’s bold challenge to the established power structures that people of color and women in america, have a right to be seen and heard. she was bold, badass, unbought and unbossed. 
long live the spirit of this great woman and freedom fighter.

text:
company values are your tools, they’re not just rules. they should be lived and breathed in the day-to-day working environment.
setting clear and consistent company values is crucial for defining acceptable and unacceptable workplace behaviours.
you’re setting expectations, and ensuring everyone understands, respects and upholds these expectations. you’re also setting values against which performance should be determined – it’s not just about numbers and targets. when someone’s behaviour is at odds with the business values, it’s a red flag.  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur

text:
being african this issue hits very close to heart. the society has burdened us women with so much responsibility. we judge women for sour marriage relationships, for failed marriages and even for not getting married. many at times we see it as the woman’s fault for her not being married. usually it is compounded to one major reason -she is not prepared for it. 
share your thoughts on the blog☝️. link in bio! -
do have a lovely day!🤗💋
-

@sayno_unite and @unwomen’s 16 days of activism are approaching! each day, we’ll share a talking point to help you spark a conversation about eliminating gender-based and interpersonal violence.

text:
every individual has there own experiences as a child.. someone has good memories and someone has bad/worst. as a parent i discuss with my children about good touch and bad touch, how to be safe and what to be done if something/ someone is bad. 
i would like to ask every parent who read my message to discuss with their children (girl/boy) about good and bad touch. this is the first step to make them understand what is right and wrong. 
i always wanted to support and help children to be mentally strong. so i have chosen my platform to educate children about child abuse and also teach them how to protect them from the abuser.

stay tuned to @swechalaya to know how to protect our children from abuse!!

text:
the group exhibition “mademoiselle” which opened its doors on 21 july 2018 at the crac occitanie in sète brings together a generation of international women artists who explore the issues and paradoxes of being a young woman today. as curator tara londi explains, “it is with a candid or calculated disregard for conventions and taboos that the artists expose the convergence of diverse feminist histories with other aspects of identity politics and social critique, supplanting the concept of a singular feminist narrative, questioning the myth of shared womanhood, and identifying contemporary obstacles for women’s emancipation.”
-
l'exposition collective “mademoiselle” qui a ouvert ses portes le 21 juillet 2018 au crac occitanie à sète rassemble une nouvelle génération de femmes artistes internationales, explorant les enjeux et paradoxes liés à la féminité contemporaine. comme l’explique la commissaire tara londi, « c’est avec un certain dédain pour les conventions et les tabous (naïf ou pas), que ces artistes travaillent à la convergence entre ces diverses histoires du féminisme et d’autres aspects de la politique et de la critique sociale, allant au-delà d’un récit féministe unique, pointant ainsi les obstacles qui se dressent devant l’émancipation des femmes. »
-
video credit: gery georgieva, rodopska beyonce, 2013. screening view at the crac occitanie.
-
@taralondi @_gery_georgieva @crac_occitanie @beyonce #gerygeorgieva #beyonce #groupshow #contemporaryart #womenartists #metoo #feminism #mademoiselle #crac

text:
eating wasps is the first book i’ve read by @anitanairauthor. i finished the book in two sittings coz i couldn’t put it down. i’m drawn to stories from the sub-continent and more so if they are about women. this book had both. it has narratives by 10 women, who take you through their complex and tough lives. though some stories were hauntingly dark, in the end i was left with some sense of hope, not despair.
.
it was also a strange coincidence that i was reading this book just when the #metoo uproar broke out in india. many of these stories were similar to the ones being revealed online. now i can’t wait to read anita nair’s other books, esp. ladies coupe. soon.
.
#bookreviewsbychica #eatingwasps #anitanair #bookstagram

text:
let's form a network of people volunteering for those who need help. this is not an organization, this is not a distress app service but just a cause to make this city feel secure. we need to kill the patriarchal mindset of bullies and ignorant mindsets. a vision to see this city as:
parents and family shall be carefree if a woman from their family is outside the house regardless of time.

don't stay quiet, raise your voice. even if it's stalking, a bad touch, visual harassment or anything for that matter, it must be exposed and raise voice against.
dm for more.

#women #india #newdelhi #indianfeminism #womensafety #metoo #metoomovement #molestation #harassment #feminist #womenempowerment #patriarchy

text: on the final day of scorpio, we celebrate bjork’s birthday! in this shot by jean baptiste mondino, the polar bear symbol is resonant with scorpio’s path of developing fearlessness and strength in adversity. bjork, like many of us confronted by scorpio challenges, has faced extreme abuse of power. on the set of the 2000 film “dancer in the dark,” director lars von trier repeatedly touched her inappropriately without consent and made graphic sexual threats. “when after 2 months of this i said he had to stop the touching, he exploded and broke a chair in front of everyone on set, like someone who has always been allowed to fondle his actresses,” she said in 2017. “i didn’t comply or agree on being sexually harassed. that was then portrayed as me being difficult. if being difficult is standing up to being treated like that, i’ll own it.” #bjork #scorpio #polarbear #fear #power #pluto #mars #metoo #sexualassault #sexualabuserecovery #spiritanimals #poweranimals #animaltotems #dailyastrology #astrology #tarot #dailytarot #tarotcards #tarotcardreading #tarotcardreader #tarottribe #strength #divinefeminine

text:
i love the inspirational quote cards. yet, i’ve heard from women who have expressed that reading them can sometimes cause fear and dread - how can they do this? is it possible? how do you move from the reality to the idea of your dream? how do you go from the nike slogan “just do it” to figuring out how to do it?

these are all very real and valid questions.  that is what i do as a coach.  i help you get out of your head (which is often filled with self-doubt and negative thoughts telling you can’t do it), set goals that are possible, develop a plan, and work with you on your journey to reaching your goals.

are you ready for a really cool transformational journey where your dreams can become your reality?  or, maybe you are wanting to care for yourself better and figure out how to like yourself (and love yourself!). if part of you is saying “let’s do this”, connect with me by clicking on the link in my bio ▶️ @denisestyer and we can discuss how.  looking forward to it! 💜

mielenkiinnolla odotan, miten #metoo -liike tulee vielä näkymään kirjallisuudessa. jennifer mathieun näpit irti! kuvaa tyttöjen voimaantumista lukiomaailmassa, jossa poikien huutelut ja huono käytös katsotaan läpi sormien, ja hehkutetaan vain koulun jalkapallojoukkuetta.

viv ihailee äitinsä nuoruutta, 90-luvun riot grrrl -liikettä ja kuuntelee bikini killin musiikkia. näistä vaikuttuneena hän päättää puuttua koulunsa asioihin tekemällä zinen, jossa kehotetaan tyttöjä nousemaan vastarintaan.

kirja käsittelee melko kepeästi tyttöihin kohdistuvaa seksuaalista väkivaltaa, mutta se ei olekaan tämän kirjan pääpointti, vaan tärkeää on nähdä, miten sorretusta joukosta yhdessä voi nousta vahva toisiaan tukeva ryhmä!

jokunen vuosi sitten ylellä tuli dokkari bikini killin laulajasta kathleen hannasta ja vaikutuin jo silloin hänestä. loistava esikuva tälle tarinalle!

#näpitirti #jennifermathieu #moxie #bikinikill #puhtimuijatpaneekampoihin #tyttöjenpuolesta #riotgrrrl

text:
...
🌿🍁🌾🍂🍃
i am truly thankful for being healthy enough this year to experience the beauty of autumn in east tennessee. october is my favorite month for sunrises, sunsets, and our changing leaves. the last few years had left me unable to appreciate these things. in october 2013, i was hospitalized on a 6 month bedrest, and facing leg amputation due to a severe mrsa infection following surgery to remove a large tumor. in october 2014, i was in and out of the hospital with brain swelling and seizures following a car accident. in october 2015, i was in an intensive outpatient dbt class, being diagnosed with an ed, and doing everything i possibly could to pass myself off as fine and avoid hospitalization. in october 2016, i was relapsing hard with the drinking and my ed. in 2017, my ptsd symptoms were triggered by the #metoo movement and i relapsed very quickly and very dangerously with my ed. i pretty much stopped functioning. honestly, i don't know how i survived that one. this summer, all my mental illnesses have hit me hard, harder than ever before, and all at once. all. at. once. but i fought, and continue to fight, harder than i ever have in my entire life. and that was how i was able to enjoy the beautiful colors of autumn this year. and i'm glad they waited until november because october was pretty tough for me. again, i'm extremely thankful for those who continue to support me and love me during the times when doing so is rather difficult.
#rawrecovery 
#thankful 
#autumn

text:
an honest and sad perspective on how to deal with the growing alcohol issue. the reality is that the majority of our lawmakers drink and profit from the alcohol addiction epidemic. no one seems to care though because the lives of alcoholic people are not valuable to society. we view this population as lacking willpower and weak, we don't even attempt to protect them from the aggressive advertising and marketing of the drug that kills them. 
they have no incentive to make changes. i dated a lobbyist for the republican party and he agreed there was zero chance of things changing with the current people in office because they are all high functioning alcoholics. he was as well and had zero interest in quitting, despite knowing he was harming himself and his children. he said he would lose his job, his friends, etc. he acted like i was crazy to get help after a missed meeting. told me i was ridiculous and dramatic and his friends covered for him, they all miss tons of meetings because of drinking and accept it as normal. when that's happening no one is speaking up for the alcoholic people and the benefits of sobriety. 
for certain reasons alcohol is deemed acceptable and we blame the individual in pain for becoming addicted rather than take a hard look at this dangerous drug and make changes to the current approach. 
it's my belief that alcohol is different from smoking and will be much harder to change the way we view alcohol. 
many men use alcohol to get laid and therefore are never going to be interested in women drinking less. this came from my brother and therapist, also a man, they told me the truth. cigarettes never benefited men like alcohol does. 
men make the laws in this country so let's not hold our breath waiting for things to change. women need to be the ones to quit drinking on their own, the government is not going to be supporting this movement, they benefit from keeping us addicted 🇺🇸😥 #godry #drydiet #godry #healthyandwealthy #sober #weightlossjourney #transformation #empoweringwomen #nohangover #noalcohol #metoo #mentalhealth #teetotaler #sober #nohangover

text: i’ve been thinking quite a bit about when to attach my face and name to @bossladycreates. i’ve never intended for this to be anonymous. i have nothing to hide. in my every day life, i’ll tell my story to *anyone* who will listen, and i want other survivors to be as unashamed to share their experiences as i am. when i started this account, i think i had so much to say that introductions and selfies kind of fell by the wayside; and now that i’m thinking about it, i know that there’s no “good” time for anything- all of it is just a leap i have to take. i’m in brooklyn right now, connecting and networking with other survivors on an incredible project spearheaded by one of my very best friends (side note: what we’re creating is extraordinary, and i cannot wait to share it with this fellow survivor community...). i’ve brought some of my leaves with me, and as i’m sitting in her bedroom typing this, in the corner of her dresser mirror are two stickers: “badass feminist” and “you are beautiful.” i love knowing that when she wakes up in the morning and first looks at herself, these words appear alongside her gorgeous face as a daily reminder of her power and strength. and she absolutely is both of those things: a badass feminist and beautiful. now that i’m seeing my own reflection here, i know that they’re true for me, too. so this is my introduction: my name is mel. i’m a survivor. i’m a badass feminist. i am beautiful. it’s so nice to finally meet you all!✨ #survivor #selfie #survivoradvocate #believesurvivors #believewomen #metoo #timesup #endrapeculture #badassfeminist #iambeautiful #artist #wip

text:
🚺rispetto🚺

questo video lo intitolo così, con questa sola parola che racchiude in sé un’infinità di significati. ciò che mi ha spinto a cimentarmi in un lavoro del genere viene dal profondo e voleva in qualche modo essere portato fuori: la visione di un mondo che oggi, ahimè, fa fatica ad assimilare un valore come  il rispetto.
ho deciso di postare questo video qualche giorno prima del 25 novembre, giornata internazionale contro la violenza sulle donne, perché credo a questo giorno. credo ai sacrifici, alle sofferenze di tante donne, uccise o maltrattate; credo alla paura, ai tentativi falliti di ricominciare ma anche al coraggio di dire basta. credo nelle donne, nelle donne che si sentono donne, nelle donne che vogliono giustizia, nelle donne che pretendono rispetto in casa, nel luogo di lavoro, per strada. e credo ovviamente negli uomini che credono nelle donne. 
per cui non festeggiate solamente l’8 marzo regalando un mazzo di fiori, non portatela a cena solo perché “oggi è il tuo giorno”. rispettala ovunque, rispettala sempre!

ho cercato di essere più coincisa possibile con la speranza che questo piccolo lavoro faccia riflettere chiunque. spero anche di vedere oltre che molte donne anche tanti uomini condividere questo video perché realmente supportano questa causa.

per finire, ringrazio la @street_school_brindisi per avermi permesso di realizzare questo filmato e a tutti i ballerini della scuola per aver condiviso con me un pezzetto del mio cuore. ringrazio omar e teddy per il grande aiuto nelle riprese. 
grazie grazie grazie <3

régine michelle jean-charles is a black feminist literary scholar and cultural critic specializing in francophone studies. her scholarship and teaching on world literatures in french includes work on black france, sub-saharan africa, haiti and the haitian diaspora. she is currently associate professor of romance languages and literatures and african and african diaspora studies at boston college. she holds a ba from the university of pennsylvania in french and african and african diaspora studies, and an am and phd in romance languages and literatures from harvard university.  she has received fellowships from the ford foundation, the mellon mays foundation and the woodrow wilson foundation.
her first book, conflict bodies:  the politics of rape representation in the francophone imaginary (columbus: ohio state university press, 2014) examines theoretical, visual, and literary texts that challenge the dominant views of sexual violence.  she has authored numerous scholarly articles that have appeared in edited volumes and peer-reviewed journals such as the journal of haitian studies, american quarterly, callaloo, french forum, journal of romance studies, research in african literatures, and small axe. her current research focuses on girlhood in contemporary haitian literature and visual culture. professor jean-charles serves as a board member of a long walk home, inc., a non-profit organization that uses art to educate, inspire, and mobilize young people to end violence against girls and women. she is also a regular contributor to media outlets like wgbh and cognoscenti, where she has weighed in on topics ranging from #metoo to issues affecting the haitian diaspora.

text:
so how do we prevent religion or belief discrimination?
talk to each other.
the festive season is in full swing and organisations debate whether or not to deck the office halls and whether to even utter the c-word – christmas – for fear of offence or reprisal. organisations need to understand, appreciate and be sensitive to the beliefs of their employees, but most importantly talk to your people, cultivate that culture of openness and respect.
indeed, the very assumption of offence due to someone’s religion or beliefs can itself be offensive and may inadvertently lead to further isolation and marginalisation.
concerned by the reception of a dress code, policies relating to leave/holiday, working patterns and flexible working, or whether to mark certain religious holidays or traditional celebrations? ask your people what they think.  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur

so how do we prevent religion or belief discrimination?
talk to each other.
the festive season is in full swing and organisations debate whether or not to deck the office halls and whether to even utter the c-word – christmas – for fear of offence or reprisal. organisations need to understand, appreciate and be sensitive to the beliefs of their employees, but most importantly talk to your people, cultivate that culture of openness and respect.
indeed, the very assumption of offence due to someone’s religion or beliefs can itself be offensive and may inadvertently lead to further isolation and marginalisation.
concerned by the reception of a dress code, policies relating to leave/holiday, working patterns and flexible working, or whether to mark certain religious holidays or traditional celebrations? ask your people what they think.  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur

text:
split families, sharing can be hard. i get it. even if we know they are having fun and super loved the sharing part is hard. if you’re missing some kiddos this week because they are baby daddying or baby mama-ing know you aren’t alone. •
•
tips: 👉🏼keep it simple. 👉🏼don’t overcomplicate the already difficult situation by over thinking. 👉🏼plan a special holiday celebration upon their return! it’s just a date on the calendar. doesn’t mean you can’t have another feast a different day! 👉🏼remember that this holiday is all about the gratitude. stay aware of how you can show gratitude. 👉🏼lead with your heart and care for your heart through the process without any self judgement for any of your feelings regardless of how “rational” they feel. •
•
missing this monster a lot this week. his crazy amazing loud rambunctious presence is definitely noticeably absent. 
we got this friends! 🦃💕🙌🏼❤️
